SIMPLE: wrist
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wrist
<hw>Wrist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>wriste</ets>,
<ets>wrist</ets>, AS. <ets>wrist</ets>; akin to OFries.
<ets>wriust</ets>, LG. <ets>wrist</ets>, G. <ets>rist</ets> wrist,
instep, Icel. <ets>rist</ets> instep, Dan. & Sw. <ets>vrist</ets>, and
perhaps to E. <ets>writhe</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The joint, or the region of the
joint, between the hand and the arm; the carpus. See
<er>Carpus</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He took me by the <qex>wrist</qex>, and held me hard.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <def>A stud or pin which forms a
journal; -- also called <altname>wrist pin</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Bridle wrist</b></col>, <cd>the wrist of the left hand,
in which a horseman holds the bridle.</cd> -- <col><b>Wrist
clonus</b></col>. <ety>[NL. <ets>clonus</ets>, fr. Gr. <?/. See
<er>Clonic</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <cd>A series of quickly
alternating movements of flexion and extension of the wrist, produced in
some cases of nervous disease by suddenly bending the hand back upon the
forearm.</cd> -- <col><b>Wrist drop</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>,
<cd>paralysis of the extensor muscles of the hand, affecting the hand so
that when an attempt is made to hold it out in line with the forearm
with the palm down, the hand drops. It is chiefly due to plumbism.
Called also <altname>hand drop</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Wrist
plate</b></col> <fld>(Steam Engine)</fld>, <cd>a swinging plate bearing
two or more wrists, for operating the valves.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wristband</ent>⟦br⟧
